  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Rain on the Twenty-Third Day of the Third Month
  author: Choe Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Last year the seasons turned against us—
    no rain when farmers needed to plant seedlings.
    The people fell into hunger's pit,
    and when they looked at each other, their faces grew pale.

    This spring too brings drought again.
    We clasp our hands in worry over the failing year.
    The well runs dry to blue mud,
    and the morning sun burns red as blood.

    The roads are strewn with the starved,
    the fields cannot yield silk or grain.
    I, lazy as always, wake late,
    lying in my thatched hall at dawn.

    Then comes the scent of rain, whisper-soft,
    and suddenly the eaves sing out in drops.
    I startle awake, push back my pillow,
    throw open the window in wild delight.

    The willows' banks glisten with verdant brows,
    the flowering hollows dress in crimson.
    All of nature glistens with rebirth,
    each blade and bloom exhales its fragrance.

    Now I understand the heart of Heaven—
    it does not abandon the hopes of its people.
    The plow and harrow fill the southern fields,
    and I can already count a thousand granaries full.

    Why should I complain of my leaking roof's umbrella?
    I have already forgotten my hunger.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 薝 (châm) refers to the eaves or rafters of a roof, and 琅琅 (rang-rang) is the onomatopoeia for the sound of rain. Together they suggest the patter of rain on the eaves.
  - key: ''
    value: 耒耜 (lei-si) refers to traditional farming implements—the wooden plow and harrow—symbols of agricultural abundance.
